recordings.file-name: XC196848-Chiffchaff song, then chitters C'Burn 2 June 2014 0649hrs.mp3
recordings.rmk: Chiffchaff singing high among Beech trees. As well as broadcasting classic song, the characteristic grating 'chit-it ... chit-it' phrase (consisting of a variable number of repetitions and with a Linnet-like quality) than is often interjected between series of 'chiffchaff' notes is given at the end of a stream of song (0:08). The insertion of, as I call them, 'chittering' notes among song appears to be random. Some birds insert them, others do not. I do not know their function but it often seems that they might reflect a level of excitement or unease. Another possibility is that the note is used to oomph up the song burst, either to out-sing a rival or to add more gusto to impress a female. On XC196846 a male inserts chittering between every verse. In doing so, this bird was atypical and seemed piqued by something, possibly a cat that was visible nearby when the recording was made.

these out of range birds are very territorial found on 29.4.13 by Noam Weiss and Yoav Perlman and were supposed to be Phylloscopus sindianus (Sp. that breeds in Turkey)

it is now quite cleer that thise are not Mountain Chiffchafs but still Sub Sp. is not clear
